05287nam a22007815i 9781503614383DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020021118  a97815036143837 a10.1515/97815036143832doi  a(DE-B1597)574735  a(OCoLC)1233040665  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aPS379b.E88 2021 4aPS379b.E88 2021 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a813/.54092231 aEsteve, Mary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIncremental Realism :bPostwar American Fiction, Happiness, and Welfare-State Liberalism /cMary Esteve. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost*4500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Symbolic Economy of Postwar American Happiness -- t1 The Art, Sociology, and Library Politics of Happiness in Early Philip Roth -- t2 Gwendolyn Brooks and the Welfare State -- t3 Queer Consumerism, Straight Happiness: Patricia Highsmith’s “Right Economy” -- t4 Countries of Health -- t5 Writing Mute Liberalism: Peter Taylor, the South, and Journeyman Happiness -- tCoda: The Politics of Contemporary Happiness -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe postwar US political imagination coalesced around a quintessential midcentury American trope: happiness. In Incremental Realism, Mary Esteve offers a bold, revisionist literary and cultural history of efforts undertaken by literary realists, public intellectuals, and policy activists to advance the value of public institutions and the claims of socioeconomic justice. Esteve specifically focuses on era-defining authors of realist fiction—including Philip Roth, Gwendolyn Brooks, Patricia Highsmith, Paula Fox, Peter Taylor, and Mary McCarthy—who mobilized the trope of happiness to reinforce the crucial value of public institutions, such as the public library, and the importance of pursuing socioeconomic justice, as envisioned by the United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights and welfare-state liberals. In addition to embracing specific symbols of happiness, these writers also developed narrative modes—what Esteve calls "incremental realism"—that made justifiable the claims of disadvantaged Americans on the nation-state and promoted a small-canvas aesthetics of moderation. With this powerful demonstration of the way postwar literary fiction linked the era's familiar trope of happiness to political arguments about socioeconomic fairness and individual flourishing, Esteve enlarges our sense of the postwar liberal imagination and its attentiveness to better, possible worlds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAuthors, AmericanxPolitical and social views. 0aHappiness in literature. 0aLiberalism in literature. 0aRealism in literature. 0aWelfare state in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican cultural history.  ahappiness.  aincremental realism.  aliberalism.  apostwar American fiction.  apublic institutions.  asocioeconomic justice.  awelfare state.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishz978311075412408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021z9783110753899oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Comple